english:
  title: Record of the Tower of Vanquishing the Enemy
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My friend Jeong Jun, Soo-hong, served as an official in the Provincial Chancellery before being sent as magistrate to Anseong. His governance proved effective and the people flourished under his care. When he renovated the eastern tower of the official residence, he sent Jeong Han, the director of the local academy, to the capital with a letter to my house at Yangchon. The letter read:

    "This tower was originally built when Shin Jun, In-do of Geochan, served as magistrate. In the year Xinchao of the Zhizheng era, the Red Bandits captured Songdo and the King fled. The bandits sent an advance force claiming to be emissaries, ravaging the provinces. From here northward, more than thirty districts surrendered at mere rumor of their approach. Some officials even dressed in their formal robes to greet them. Like a tide that swallows the heavens, their momentum swept southward, and it seemed the entire nation would perish with none to stop them. Yet this district alone rose up with righteous spirit. We feigned surrender and held a banquet, intoxicating the enemy before destroying them utterly. Thus the bandits never pressed further south, and the nation was able to achieve its restoration. For this righteous valor, the district was elevated in rank. The following year, in Gyemyo, Shin Jun came and built this tower to commemorate both the valor shown against the enemy and the honor of this elevation. Yet though he built it, he gave it no name, and recorded nothing of these events for posterity. Now more than thirty-six years have passed. The old have departed, the vigorous have grown old. If more time passes, future generations will have no way to know of this district's service to the nation or the significance of this tower. We have now repaired it in the old manner, replacing decay with durability, and named it 'Vanquishing the Enemy.' I seek your brush to create a lasting record, so that the people of this district and their descendants never forget the valor of their ancestors.

    "Near at hand, mountains rise to the northeast, crowned with verdant pines and towering trees that gather in mysterious depth. To the south flows a great river from east to west. A dozen or more petty officials' houses dot the inner landscape like scattered points. Broad fields stretching dozens of acres extend beyond, with mulberry and hemp lining the boundaries, grain and millet filling the terraces. In spring they plow, in summer they weed, departing at dawn and returning at dusk. Any townsperson with business within can lean from this tower and survey all below. In the distance, the peaks of Cheonheung and Cheongryong Mountains appear as if peering down, bowing in courtesy, arrayed like a folding screen with no end in sight. Such is the splendor of this tower. In ancient times, Han Yu wrote of the Teng Pavilion without ever ascending it, so I hope you will not decline on account of not having witnessed this place with your own eyes."

    I reflect that during the five hundred years of Wang rule over Goryeo, no calamities were more severe than two: the invasion of Hadan in the year Gyeongsin under King Chungnyeol, and the Red Bandit uprising in Sinchuk under King Gongmin. When Taelyeong fell and Hadan swept through, the outer districts seemed mere empty lands, yet when the enemy reached Wonju, a common man named Chung-gap wielded his arm and cried out with such force that he destroyed them utterly—even now we honor his memory. When Songdo fell and the Red Bandits grew fierce, dividing their forces southward, all places surrendered at mere rumor, unable to withstand the torrential surge of their advance. Yet the people of this district, devoted to their nation, annihilated the invaders and stood like a great dike, stemming the flood's overflow. Their merit and valor rival Chung-gap's, and deserve to be proclaimed throughout all ages as an eternal exhortation.

    Alas, loyalty and righteousness are the great virtues of humanity and the foundation of good governance. Jeong Jun, possessed early of the qualities of filial devotion and loyalty, has cultivated the study of benevolence and rightness. His lofty aspirations and unwavering integrity are truly eminent and singular. Now in his governance of this district, he first bore witness to these events and specially inscribed this name upon this tower to inspire future generations without end. This too is worthy of record. When those who come after climb this tower and contemplate the valor of their ancestors and the aspirations of Jeong Jun, if their hearts are moved by the innate love of virtue, then loyal and righteous scholars will emerge in abundance. What benefit might this bring to the realm's transformation?

    Some say: "The victory over enemies appears only in times of national peril—a thing that occurs but rarely across generations. How then can those moved by such examples display their virtue?" I answer: "While deeds differ in magnitude, their principle is the same. All desires that harm the heavenly principle in our hearts are enemies. Greed harms integrity, harshness harms benevolence, self-interest harms justice, crookedness harms rectitude. All are enemies that we must overcome and master. Extending this principle to all things, in our daily conduct, wherever we triumph over our selfish nature to restore the heavenly principle, we perform the conquest of enemies. Righteousness is inexhaustible in its application. Confucius told Yan Hui: 'To conquer oneself and return to propriety—this is benevolence.' Let this be our practice, and Jeong Jun's aspirations will nearly be fulfilled."

    This record is written in the thirty-first year of Hongwu, in the year of the Blue Dragon, on the full moon of the fifth month after that year.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Red Bandits' (紅賊) were a peasant rebellion in Yuan China that extended their campaigns into Goryeo in the mid-14th century, posing an existential threat to the kingdom.
    - Hadan refers to the Mongolian general whose invasions during the reign of King Chungnyeol represented another major threat to Goryeo's sovereignty.
    - The phrase 'conquering oneself and returning to propriety' (克己復禮) references Confucius's definition of benevolence and represents the ethical extension of military valor to personal moral cultivation.
    - The work is dated to 1368 CE (the 31st year of Hongwu, the founding emperor of Ming China), placing it in the early period of Ming rule.
